04780nam a22007095i 9783110426953DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20172018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831104269537 a10.1515/97831104269532doi  a(DE-B1597)451606  a(OCoLC)1013957440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a9302231 aSarri, Antonia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaterial Aspects of Letter Writing in the Graeco-Roman World :bc. 500 BC - c. AD 300 /cAntonia Sarri. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2017] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 388 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMateriale Textkulturen ,x2198-6932 ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Development of the Ancient Letter -- t2. Evidence -- t3. Format and Layout -- t4. Authentication -- tAppendices -- tAppendix I: Letters in Archives -- tAppendix II: Dimensions of Letters -- tAppendix III: Letters with Handshifts -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aLetter writing was widespread in the Graeco-Roman world, as indicated by the large number of surviving letters and their extensive coverage of all social categories. Despite a large amount of work that has been done on the topic of ancient epistolography, material and formatting conventions have remained underexplored, mainly due to the difficulty of accessing images of letters in the past. Thanks to the increasing availability of digital images and the appearance of more detailed and sophisticated editions, we are now in a position to study such aspects. This book examines the development of letter writing conventions from the archaic to Roman times, and is based on a wide corpus of letters that survive on their original material substrates. The bulk of the material is from Egypt, but the study takes account of comparative evidence from other regions of the Graeco-Roman world. Through analysis of developments in the use of letters, variations in formatting conventions, layout and authentication patterns according to the sociocultural background and communicational needs of writers, this book sheds light on changing trends in epistolary practice in Graeco-Roman society over a period of roughly eight hundred years. This book will appeal to scholars of Epistolography, Papyrology, Palaeography, Classics, Cultural History of the Graeco-Roman World.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGreek lettersxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin lettersxHistory and criticism. 4aBriefe. 4aEpistolografie. 4aGriechisch-Römisches Ägypten. 4aPapyrus. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aEpistolography.  aGraeco-Roman Egypt.  aLetters.  apapyrus.2 aDeutsche Forschungsgemeinschaftefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2018 Part 1z978311076248808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z97831107195500 cEPUBz97831104234880 cprintz978311042694640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110426953zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110426953zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110426953/original  a978-3-11-071955-0 DG Plus eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-1